Modern glibc (>= 2.36, e.g. Ubuntu 22.04+) provides arc4random()/arc4random_buf()
but not the legacy BSD arc4random_addrandom()/arc4random_stir() reseed hooks.
evutil_secure_rng_add_bytes() calls arc4random_addrandom() unconditionally,
regardless of which PRNG backend the rest of this file selected — this breaks
the final link of anything linking libevent (undefined reference) on any libc
missing just that one legacy symbol.

glibc's arc4random()/arc4random_buf() already reseed themselves internally
(from the kernel CSPRNG) without needing external entropy hints, so making
this a no-op when EVENT__HAVE_ARC4RANDOM is set (i.e. we're using the
system's real arc4random family, not libevent's own bundled fallback further
down in this same file, which still has its own working arc4random_addrandom)
is safe: this call was always just a hint, its absence does not weaken the
actual randomness source used for anything else in the codebase.

--- a/evutil_rand.c
+++ b/evutil_rand.c
@@ -195,8 +195,16 @@
 void
 evutil_secure_rng_add_bytes(const char *buf, size_t n)
 {
+#ifdef EVENT__HAVE_ARC4RANDOM
+	/* Using the system arc4random() family: it already self-reseeds
+	 * internally, and modern glibc doesn't expose the legacy
+	 * arc4random_addrandom() hook this call would otherwise need. */
+	(void)buf;
+	(void)n;
+#else
 	arc4random_addrandom((unsigned char*)buf,
 	    n>(size_t)INT_MAX ? INT_MAX : (int)n);
+#endif
 }

 void
